Please note, (at least as of 19.1) commenting out `dlib::shape_predictor_trainer` in `dlib/image_processing/shape_predictor.h` fixes the issue.

- [ ] intersection_with(): This method is like _.intersection except that it accepts comparator which is invoked to compare elements of arrays.
Syntax: `intersection_with(arrayA, arrayB, logical_oprator)`
Example: 
```python
>>> a = [{ 'x': 1, 'y': 2 }, { 'x': 2, 'y': 1 }];
>>> b = [{ 'x': 1, 'y': 1 }, { 'x': 1, 'y': 2 }];
>>> intersection_with(a, b, is);
[{ 'x': 1, 'y': 2 }]
```
In JS we have various equality operators such as .isEqual, .isGreater, etc. We can have some keywords or we can use logical operators directly.

Apologies if I am incorrectly using the API, but it seems to me that when using the following code:

```
@ns.response(code=HTTPStatus.CONFLICT, description='Cannot delete because X')
def delete(self, id):
   if(...)
        ns.abort(HTTPStatus.CONFLICT)
```

will produce a generic description (or none at all) when returning the HTTP error code.

Wouldn't it make sense, when no `message` is provided to `Namespace.abort()` to automatically use the `description` provided in `Namespace.response()`?

